{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17517178","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17517178"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:51:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:51:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12774"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12774","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12774"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.39,0.52,0.03,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5218"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104879"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5218","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5218"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12774"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87265"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1094"},{"type":"tags","id":"1153"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"9590"},{"type":"tags","id":"12917"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8855"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8962"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14298"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33943"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104879","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104879"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old man presents with confusion and is subsequently admitted to ICU due to hyponatraemia (Na 112 mmol/L (135-145)). His history includes hypertension for which he takes amlodipine. On presentation, his blood pressure is 97/45 mmHg. His JVP is not visible lying down. He has very dry mucous membranes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOver the next two days in ICU his sodium level improves (Na 135 mmol/L). However, he begins to develop dysphagia and diplopia. On examination, he has bilateral 6th nerve palsies and a positive Babinski\u0027s sign on the left.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following treatments should have been implemented to prevent the patient\u0027s current problem?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Administration of 0.9% NaCl to rapidly correct the Na by 10-12 mmol in the first hour","Administration of 0.9% NaCl to slowly correct the Na by 4-6mmol in the first 24 hours","Administration of 3% NaCl to achieve an initial increase of 4-8mmol, with a 24 hour maximum of 10mmol in the first 24 hours","Administration of 23.4% NaCl to achieve an initial increase of 12mmol and a 24 hour aim of normalising serum Na","Administration of 23.4% NaCl to slowly normalise the serum sodium over the first 24 hours"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has developed osmotic demyelination syndrome (ODS), a serious complication of overly rapid correction of severe hyponatraemia. ODS includes both central pontine myelinolysis (CPM) and extrapontine myelinolysis (EPM). CPM typically presents with dysarthria, dysphagia, diplopia, and quadriparesis due to demyelination of the central pons, while EPM may cause movement disorders (e.g., parkinsonism), catatonia, and behavioural changes when basal ganglia or other extrapontine structures are affected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has features suggestive of both central pontine myelinolysis (e.g. dysphagia, diplopia, bilateral sixth nerve palsies) and extrapontine myelinolysis (e.g. Babinski\u2019s sign indicating corticospinal tract involvement), which together reflect osmotic demyelination syndrome. The presence of both CPM and EPM is associated with more extensive demyelination and typically indicates a more severe clinical course and poorer prognosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETo avoid ODS, sodium should be corrected slowly. The \u003Cem\u003EAustralian Therapeutic Guidelines\u003C/em\u003E recommend using \u003Cstrong\u003E3% hypertonic saline\u003C/strong\u003E for severe hyponatraemia (e.g., Na \u0026lt;120 mmol/L) with a correction target of \u003Cstrong\u003E4\u20138 mmol/L in the first 24 hours\u003C/strong\u003E, and 4\u20136 mmol/L in those with additional risk factors for developing central pontine myelinolysis, such as:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENa \u0026lt; 105 mmol/L,\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ehypokalaemia,\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ealcoholism,\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Emalnutrition or\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eadvanced liver disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministration of 0.9% NaCl to slowly correct Na \u003C/strong\u003Eis appropriate for mild/moderate hyponatraemia secondary to hypovolaemia. For sodium levels Na \u0026lt; 120, a hypertonic solution is required.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Rapidly correcting hyponatraemia puts patients at risk of developing central pontine myelinolysis.","Correction of severe hyponatraemia (\u003C120 mmol/L) should be with 3% sodium chloride (hypertonic saline) to achieve an initial target of no more than 120 mmol/L"],"references":["Lambeck J, Hieber M, Dre\u00dfing A, Niesen WD. Central pontine myelinosis and osmotic demyelination syndrome. Deutsches \u00c4rzteblatt International. 2019 Sep;116(35-36):600."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87265"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12774"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"